{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:11:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:11:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17798"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17798"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0,0.03,0.03,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79266"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10512"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64597"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9929"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79266"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral chemoreceptors play a vital role in respiratory control by monitoring blood gas composition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary stimulus detected by peripheral chemoreceptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arterial oxygen tension","Arterial blood temperature","Cerebrospinal fluid pH","Blood bicarbonate concentration","Arterial carbon dioxide tension"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary stimulus for peripheral chemoreceptors is \u003Cstrong\u003Earterial oxygen tension\u003C/strong\u003E. Located in the carotid and aortic bodies, these specialised sensors are most sensitive to changes in arterial oxygen levels, particularly when PaO2 falls below 60 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial blood temperature\u003C/strong\u003E - Temperature is detected by thermoreceptors, not chemoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrospinal fluid pH\u003C/strong\u003E - This is monitored by central chemoreceptors, not peripheral ones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood bicarbonate concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - Peripheral chemoreceptors do not directly sense bicarbonate levels\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial carbon dioxide tension\u003C/strong\u003E - While peripheral chemoreceptors do respond to increased carbon dioxide, this is primarily detected by central chemoreceptors in the medulla\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen activated by hypoxaemia, peripheral chemoreceptors increase both respiratory rate and tidal volume through afferent signals to the respiratory centres in the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies primarily detect changes in arterial oxygen tension.","Peripheral chemoreceptors also respond to changes in arterial pH and carbon dioxide, but are less sensitive to these than central chemoreceptors.","The carotid bodies provide approximately 95% of the peripheral chemoreceptor response."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemR